    "body": ":backlog:\r\n\r\n## Problem\r\n\r\n`nvim_exec_autocmds({ buf = ... })` already uses the passed buffer for (`<abuf>`, buffer-local autocommands, etc.), but it doesn't execute *in* that buffer's context.\r\n\r\nA minimal example explains it best:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nlocal target = vim.api.nvim_create_buf(false, true)\r\nlocal caller = vim.api.nvim_create_buf(false, true)\r\n\r\nvim.api.nvim_set_current_buf(caller)\r\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd('SomeEvents', {\r\n  buffer = target,\r\n  callback = function()\r\n    print(vim.fn.expand('<abuf>'), vim.api.nvim_get_current_buf())\r\n  end,\r\n})\r\n\r\nvim.api.nvim_exec_autocmds('SomeEvent', { buf = target })\r\n\r\n-- (<abuf> == target) != (current_buf == caller)\r\n```\r\n\r\nFixes #35393.\r\n\r\n## Solution\r\n\r\nThe tempting & suggested fix is to wrap w/ `aucmd_prepbuf()` / `aucmd_restbuf()` but this is not right. Consider the following example: \r\n\r\n```lua\r\nlocal target = vim.api.nvim_create_buf(false, false)\r\nlocal caller = vim.api.nvim_create_buf(false, false)\r\n\r\nvim.api.nvim_set_current_buf(caller)\r\nvim.cmd.split()\r\nvim.api.nvim_set_current_buf(target)\r\nlocal left = vim.api.nvim_get_current_win()\r\nvim.cmd.vsplit()\r\nlocal right = vim.api.nvim_get_current_win()\r\nvim.cmd.wincmd('j')\r\nvim.api.nvim_set_current_buf(caller)\r\n\r\nlocal chosen = vim.api.nvim_buf_call(target, function()\r\n  return vim.api.nvim_get_current_win()\r\nend)\r\nlocal other = chosen == left and right or left\r\n\r\nvim.wo[chosen].eventignorewin = 'CursorHold'\r\nvim.wo[other].eventignorewin = ''\r\n\r\nvim.g.fired = 0\r\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd('CursorHold', {\r\n  buffer = target,\r\n  callback = function() vim.g.fired = vim.g.fired + 1 end,\r\n})\r\n\r\nvim.api.nvim_exec_autocmds('CursorHold', { buf = target })\r\nprint(vim.g.fired)  -- 1\r\n```\r\n\r\nHere the target buffer is visible in two windows `left` and `right` but only one of them ignores `CursorHold` via `eventignorewin`. Currently, the full window set is seen and the event fires (one window allows it). With the erroneous fix, `aucmd_prepbuf()` picks a window up front and doesn't ask all windows whether it is allowed, which can incorrectly suppress the autocmd.\r\n\r\nInstead, add a separate buffer-context path for buffer-specific `nvim_exec_autocmds()` and delay the context switch until dispatch executes. This preserves the described semantics (callbacks, modelines run in the buffer too).\r\n\r\n***NOTE***: I am not a C dev. This is the most C that I have written in the last year. It is also the most complex issue I have fixed so far so I'm almost certainly missing some things.",
